A year later, Albert Einstein wrote his famous equation, E=mc2,** which gave mathematical expression to the relationship between matter and energy.1 Research during the 1930's on the physics of nuclear fission convinced *Mr. Gielecki is a supervisory economist in the Energy Information Administration's (EIA's) Office of Coal, Nuclear, Electric and Alternate Fuels.
